            <section class="prose mt-8">
              <h2>Infusion rate formulas</h2>
              <p>
                Infusion rate describes how fast a fluid or medication is
                delivered intravenously. It can be expressed as mL/hr, gtt/min
                (drops per minute), or as a weight-based dose such as
                mcg/kg/min.
              </p>

              <h3>1. Volume and time → mL/hr</h3>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Formula</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{Rate (mL/hr)} = \frac{\text{Volume (mL)}}{\text{Time
                  (hr)}} \]
                </p>
              </div>
              <p><strong>Example:</strong> 500 mL over 4 hours</p>
              <p>\[ \text{Rate} = \frac{500}{4} = 125 \text{ mL/hr} \]</p>

              <h3>2. mL/hr → gtt/min (drip rate)</h3>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Formula</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{gtt/min} = \frac{\text{mL/hr} \times \text{drop
                  factor (gtt/mL)}}{60} \]
                </p>
              </div>
              <p><strong>Example:</strong> 120 mL/hr with a 20 gtt/mL set</p>
              <p>
                \[ \text{gtt/min} = \frac{120 \times 20}{60} = 40 \text{
                gtt/min} \]
              </p>

              <h3>3. Weight-based infusion (mcg/kg/min)</h3>
              <p>First calculate the concentration of the drug in the bag:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  \[ \text{Concentration (mcg/mL)} = \frac{\text{Drug amount
                  (mcg)}}{\text{Volume (mL)}} \]
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>Then calculate the pump rate:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  \[ \text{Rate (mL/hr)} = \frac{\text{Dose (mcg/kg/min)} \times
                  \text{Weight (kg)} \times 60}{\text{Concentration (mcg/mL)}}
                  \]
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                <strong>Example:</strong> 5 mcg/kg/min for a 70 kg patient, bag
                contains 200 mg in 250 mL.
              </p>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  Convert 200 mg to mcg: \(200 \times 1000 = 200{,}000\) mcg.
                </li>
                <li>Concentration: \(200{,}000 \div 250 = 800\) mcg/mL.</li>
                <li>
                  Rate: \[ \text{Rate} = \frac{5 \times 70 \times 60}{800} =
                  \frac{21{,}000}{800} \approx 26.25 \text{ mL/hr} \]
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h3>4. Dose-based infusion (mg/hr or mcg/min)</h3>
              <p>Again, start with the concentration:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  \[ \text{Concentration (mg/mL)} = \frac{\text{Drug amount
                  (mg)}}{\text{Volume (mL)}} \]
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>Then:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  \[ \text{Rate (mL/hr)} = \frac{\text{Dose
                  (mg/hr)}}{\text{Concentration (mg/mL)}} \]
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>If the dose is in mcg/min, convert to mg/hr first:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  \[ \text{Dose (mg/hr)} = \frac{\text{Dose (mcg/min)} \times
                  60}{1000} \]
                </p>
              </div>

              <h2>Common pitfalls and safety tips</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Always check units</strong>: mg vs mcg, kg vs lb, hr
                  vs min.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Use actual body weight vs ideal body weight</strong>
                  according to your protocol and drug monograph.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>High-risk medications</strong> (e.g., vasoactive
                  drugs, insulin, heparin) usually require an independent
                  double-check.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Round sensibly</strong>: drip rates are usually
                  rounded to the nearest whole gtt/min; pump rates may be
                  rounded to 0.1–1 mL/hr depending on policy.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Monitor the patient</strong> and IV site regularly for
                  signs of infiltration, extravasation, or adverse effects.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>

              <h3>How do I choose the correct drop factor?</h3>
              <p>
                The drop factor (gtt/mL) is printed on the IV tubing package.
                Macrodrip sets are often 10, 15, or 20 gtt/mL and are used for
                faster infusions. Microdrip sets are usually 60 gtt/mL and are
                used when precise control is needed (e.g., pediatrics, potent
                drugs).
              </p>

              <h3>When should I use mcg/kg/min instead of mg/hr?</h3>
              <p>
                Weight-based units like mcg/kg/min are common for vasoactive
                infusions (e.g., dopamine, norepinephrine), some sedatives, and
                other drugs where dose must be individualized by body weight.
                Fixed mg/hr doses are more common for standard adult infusions
                where weight-based titration is not required.
              </p>

              <h3>
                Can this calculator replace my hospital’s infusion charts?
              </h3>
              <p>
                No. This calculator is a support tool. Always follow your
                hospital’s infusion protocols, drug monographs, and local
                policies. If there is any discrepancy, institutional guidance
                takes priority.
              </p>
